issue.body:

<!-- Check all that apply [x] -->

- [x ] I have read through the manual page (`man fzf`)
- [x ] I have the latest version of fzf
- [x ] I have searched through the existing issues

## Info

- OS
    - [ x] Linux
    - [ ] Mac OS X
    - [ ] Windows
    - [ ] Etc.
- Shell
    - [ ] bash
    - [ ] zsh
    - [ ] fish
    
## Problem / Steps to reproduce

I have been using fzf just for searching stuff in terminal, like when I want to search a command after installing fzf I could find it easily via ctr+R like:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/62394093/112744211-f6cf8580-8f6b-11eb-8378-d92d7f8642fe.png)
 but now on ubuntu 20.04 when I do ctr+R it does not show me the options anymore and it is like normal ctr+R in the terminal, what should I do?

comment.body:
I noticed this in the readme:
```
    âš ï¸ Key bindings (CTRL-T / CTRL-R / ALT-C) and fuzzy auto-completion may not be enabled by default.

    Refer to the package documentation for more information. (e.g. apt-cache show fzf)
```

You need the following in your `.bashrc` after `bash_completion`
```
[ -f ~/.fzf.bash ] && source ~/.fzf.bash
```

Successfully deployed to the following URLs:

* [uno-score-r-kojima.vercel.app](https://uno-score-r-kojima.vercel.app)  
* [uno-score-git-master-r-kojima.vercel.app](https://uno-score-git-master-r-kojima.vercel.app)  
* [uno-score.vercel.app](https://uno-score.vercel.app)  
* [uno.phoneportal.net](https://uno.phoneportal.net)
